      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "@algorithmicCoder  There is no built-in tree structure in java, besides <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/api/java/util/TreeMap.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">TreeMap</a>/TreeSet, which is for sorting keys, and <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/1.5/docs/api/javax/swing/tree/DefaultTreeModel.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">DefaultTreeModel</a>, which is usually used with <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/components/tree.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JTree</a>. I think your design of a map of A objects to a group of B objects works fine."
    } ],
